            <entry xml:id="entry_kakon" xml:lang="os">
                <form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma"><orth>kakon</orth></form>
                <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>kokojnæ</orth><form type="variant"><orth>koko</orth></form></form>
                <sense xml:id="sense_d2050e74"><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                        <q>терновник</q>
                    </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                        <q>blackthorn</q>
                    </abv:tr></sense>
                <re xml:id="re_d2050e84">
                    <form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma"><orth>kakon synʒ</orth></form>
                    <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>kokojni sinʒæ</orth><form type="variant"><orth>koko sinʒæ</orth></form></form>
                </re>
                <abv:exampleGrp>
                    <abv:example xml:id="example_d2050e97" xml:lang="os-x-digor">
                        <usg><lang/></usg>
                        <quote>Sirdon bæxi 'ftawguti buni kokojni sinʒitæ bakodta</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>Сирдон подложил под попону лошади терновые колючки</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>Sirdon put thorns under the horsecloth</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_СОПам."/><biblScope>II
                            21</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                    <abv:example xml:id="example_d2050e119" xml:lang="os-x-digor">
                        <usg><lang/></usg>
                        <quote>aci suvællonmæ fud cæstæ, fud zærdæ ka badara, e fæxxætæd koko
                            sinʒæbæl bæǧænbadæj</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>кто отнесется к этому ребенку с дурным глазом, дурным сердцем, тот
                                пусть походит по терновнику босиком</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>may whoever who treats this child with an evil eye and a bad heart
                                walk on the blackthorn barefoot</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_СОПам."/><biblScope>II
                            177</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                    <abv:example xml:id="example_d2050e141">
                        <quote>dæ wazægdony kakon synʒ k˳y szadi<note type="comment" xml:lang="ru">из песни о Куцыкке</note><note type="comment" xml:lang="en">from a
                                song about Kutsyk</note></quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>в твоей кунацкой вырос терновник</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>blackthorn grew in your kunak room</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                    </abv:example>
                </abv:exampleGrp>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Слово представлено в угро-финских, тюркских и кавказских языках:
                        <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e165" xml:lang="hu"><lang/>
                        <w>kökény</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e170" xml:lang="hu"><w>kökönye</w>
                        <gloss><q>терновник</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e176" xml:lang="kv"><lang/>
                        <w>kokan</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e181" xml:lang="udm"><lang/>
                        <w>kekon</w>
                        <gloss><q>чемерица</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e189" xml:lang="udm"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>helleborus</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e196" xml:lang="trk" extralang="chg"><lang/>
                        <w>küküm</w>
                        <gloss><q>род сливы</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Vámbéry"/></bibl>), <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e207" xml:lang="ky"><lang/>
                        <w>küken</w>
                        <gloss><q>вишня</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Будагов"/></bibl>), <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e218" xml:lang="tr-x-anat"><lang/>
                        <w>köken</w>
                        <gloss><q>земляника</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Zenker"/></bibl>); <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e230" xml:lang="ce"><lang/>
                        <w>koka</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e235" xml:lang="krc-x-balkar"><lang/>
                        <w>kakon</w></mentioned> в %iEš-kakon%i название местности, буквально
                    „ослиный (%ieš%i) терновник (%ikakon%i)", ср. аналогичное осетинское выражение:
                    %ixæræg synʒ%i ‘ослиный терновник’. Может быть, сюда же <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e240" xml:lang="ka" dialect="ka-x-rach"><lang/>
                        <w>c’ia k’ok’onia</w>
                        <gloss><q>обрядовый костер</q></gloss></mentioned> (из терновника?)
                            (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_СМК"/><biblScope>XXI 2
                            122</biblScope></bibl>). — Если допустить, что в корне слова лежит
                        <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e252" xml:lang="trk"><lang/>
                        <w>kök</w>
                        <gloss><q>синий</q></gloss></mentioned> (что, однако, подходит не для всех
                    приведенных значений), то первоисточник следует искать в тюркских языках.
                            <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Gombocz"/><biblScope>(101)</biblScope></bibl> считает венг. %ikökény%i
                    заимствованным из <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e265" xml:lang="xbo"><lang/>
                        <w>*kükän</w></mentioned>, а восточнофинские факты, вряд ли основательно,
                    совершенно отделяет. Осетинский мог заимствовать слово как из угро-финских (ср.
                    %ipysyra%i ‘крапива’), так и из тюркских (для соответствия тюрк. %iküküm%i — ос.
                    %ikokon%i ср. тюрк. %igügüm%i — ос. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_gogon"/>
                    ‘кувшин’). О связи с др.инд. %ikakṣa-%i ‘низкий кустарник’ думать не
                    приходится.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">The word is present in Ugro-Finnic, Turkic and Caucasian
                    languages: <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e275" xml:lang="hu"><lang/>
                        <w>kökény</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e280" xml:lang="hu"><w>kökönye</w>
                        <gloss><q>blackthorn</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e286" xml:lang="kv"><lang/>
                        <w>kokan</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e291" xml:lang="udm"><lang/>
                        <w>kekon</w>
                        <gloss><q>hellebore</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e299" xml:lang="udm"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>helleborus</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e306" xml:lang="trk" extralang="chg"><lang/>
                        <w>küküm</w>
                        <gloss><q>prunus</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Vámbéry"/></bibl>), <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e317" xml:lang="ky"><lang/>
                        <w>küken</w>
                        <gloss><q>cherry</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Будагов"/></bibl>), <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e328" xml:lang="tr-x-anat"><lang/>
                        <w>köken</w>
                        <gloss><q>strawberry</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Zenker"/></bibl>); <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e340" xml:lang="ce"><lang/>
                        <w>koka</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e345" xml:lang="krc-x-balkar"><lang/>
                        <w>kakon</w></mentioned> in %iEš-kakon%i locality name, literally „donkey's
                    (%ieš%i) blackthorn (%ikakon%i)", cf. analogous Ossetic expression: %ixæræg
                    synʒ%i ‘donkey's blackthorn’. Maybe <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e350" xml:lang="ka" dialect="ka-x-rach"><lang/>
                        <w>c’ia k’ok’onia</w>
                        <gloss><q>ceremonial fire</q></gloss></mentioned> (from blackthorn?) is
                    related to %ikakon%i as well (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_СМК"/><biblScope>XXI 2 122</biblScope></bibl>). — Supposing that the root
                    contains <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e362" xml:lang="trk"><lang/>
                        <w>kök</w>
                        <gloss><q>blue</q></gloss></mentioned> (however, this is not suitable for
                    all meanings above), its source should be in Turkic languages. <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Gombocz"/><biblScope>(101)</biblScope></bibl>
                    consideres Hungarian %ikökény%i to be borrowed from <mentioned xml:id="mentioned_d2050e375" xml:lang="xbo"><lang/>
                        <w>*kükän</w></mentioned>, and he separates it from eastern-Finnish facts
                    (it is hardly so). Ossetic might have borrowed this word from Ugro-Finnic
                    languages (cf. %ipysyra%i ‘nettle’), as well as from Turkic languages (for the
                    correspondence of Turkic %iküküm%i — Ossetic %ikokon%i cf. Turkic %igügüm%i —
                    Ossetic <ref type="xr" target="#entry_gogon"/> ‘jug’). The relation with Old
                    Indic %ikakṣa-%i ‘low scrub’ is not probable.</etym>
            </entry>
